<subSubSection pageId="97" pageNumber="98" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="97.[140,1108,588,1073]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,312,659,685]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis box="[185,307,659,685]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[321,544,659,685]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wyatti">
<emphasis box="[321,544,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Psammopolia wyatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a large whitish silver-gray species with a large pale orbicular spot. The genitalia of both sexes of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[696,794,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wyatti">
<emphasis box="[696,712,695,720]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[726,794,695,720]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">wyatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the largest in the genus. The male valve has a large triangular cucullus and a flattened expanded ventral valve margin proximal to the clasper base. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[547,765,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wyatti">
<emphasis box="[547,765,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Psammopolia wyatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[906,1001,766,792]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arietis">
<emphasis box="[906,922,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[935,1001,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">arietis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
throughout its range. Differences between them are described under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[824,921,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arietis">
<emphasis box="[824,840,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[855,921,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">arietis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="97" pageNumber="98" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="97.[140,1108,588,1073]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,494,835,861]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis box="[185,336,835,861]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[503,724,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wyatti">
<emphasis box="[503,724,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Psammopolia wyatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from southern 
<collectingRegion box="[988,1075,836,862]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Oregon</collectingRegion>
to the Queen Charlotte Islands, 
<collectingRegion box="[474,675,871,897]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
. Adults fly over sand beaches, are nocturnal, and come to light. It has been collected from late May to early September.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="97.[140,1108,588,1073]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
The larva is described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Crumb SE" box="[485,655,941,968]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" refId="ref64210" refString="Crumb SE (1956) Th e larvae of the Phalaenidae. United States Department of Agriculture, Technical Bulletin 1135, Washington, D. C., 356 pp." type="book" year="1956">Crumb (1956)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Godfrey GL" box="[719,904,941,967]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" pagination="1 - 265" refId="ref64518" refString="Godfrey GL (1972) A review and reclassification of larvae of the subfamily Hadeninae (Lepidoptera, Noctuidae) of America north of Mexico. United States Department of Agriculture, Technical Bulletin, 1450: 1 - 265." type="journal article" year="1972">Godfrey (1972)</bibRefCitation>
. It feeds on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polygonales" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paronychia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Polygonum paronychia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[359,542,976,1002]" class="Reptilia" family="Anguidae" genus="Abronia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latifolia">
<emphasis box="[359,542,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Abronia latifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Less." authorityName="Less." box="[559,903,976,1003]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tanacetum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="camphoratum">
<emphasis box="[559,839,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Tanacetum camphoratum</emphasis>
Less.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[920,1044,976,1002]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
), and a grass. Th e prolegs are obsolescent except in early instars, are fused to the venter, and lack crochets. Larvae in various stages of development are found throughout the year.
</paragraph>
